INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (219, 2, '2008-08-27 16:28:44', '2008-08-27 14:28:44', 'Here you\'ll find some info about the master\'s program SEDS ((Software engineering of Distributed Systems)) in ICT ((Information and Communciation Technologie)) at KTH ((Kungliska Tekniska Högskulan)) in Stockholm, Schweden.\r\n\r\n<h2>Social Approach</h2>\r\nIf created and joined some spaces where I try to share views, ideas and problems related to my Distributed Systems studies. Here is the list for these spaces:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Our own website: <a href="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/SEDS/">The <strike>official</strike>missing SEDS forum</a></strong><br />Here it like to have the most discussion and experience since it\'s the most open one from all proprietary approaches like Facebook and Yahoo. There I can act as flexible as possible and get the most people in since they don\'t have to be shy of sharing personal or private information.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Facebook Group: <a href="http://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=31753911868">KTH » ICT » SEDS | 2008-2010</a></strong><br />Here all started. I thought using Facebook is a good idea to combine the study with social aspects. Works quite well although still too many peoply refuse to join Facebook.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Facebook Group: <a href="http://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=26119077267">SEDS Group</a></strong><br />This group is intended to share views and information among the SEDS (Software Engineering of Distributed Systems) group in KTH - The Royal Institute of Technology in Sweden. Especially after the study time to keep up with study mates or also to find master thesis ideas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>Miscellaneous</h2>\r\n<h3>Erlang - Magic Cookie</h3>\r\nIf you have ever wondered, why you can communicate to another node of your own domain\'s system without manually setting a magic cookie ((The <i>magic cookie</i> in Erlang is kind of a authentification string send over to other nodes with every message beeing send. So the receiving system can check wether to accept the message or not. How this is done in detail can be read at <a href="http://www.erlang-fr.org/erlang.org/doc/getting_started/getting_started.html#security">Erlang Security</a>.)) as an argument <code>-setcookie</code>, the answer is as followed:\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>First, the node creates a random atom as its magic cookie, but all other nodes assume the atom <code>nocookie</code> for all other nodes.</li>\r\n	<li>After the <i>auth server</i> did start (so for this case without the <code>-setcookie</code> flag), it reads a file named <code>$HOME/.erlang.cookie</code>. If the file <code>$HOME/.erlang.cookie</code> does not exist, it is created with a random string as its content. You can check and verify this your own current cookie with the command <pre lang="erlang">erlang:get_cookie().</pre> ((You can lookup information about things like this module function at <a href="http://www.erlang.org/doc/man/auth.html">Auth Module</a>)).</li>\r\n	<li>Then the function <pre lang="erlang">erlang:set_cookie(node(), CookieAtom).</pre> sets the magic cookie.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThat means, using <pre lang="erlang">erlang:set_cookie(node(), nocookie).</pre> makes a node completely acceptable to any received message from any node.', 'SEDS (Software Engineering of Distributed Systems)', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'seds-software-engineering-of-distributed-systems', '', '', '2008-11-13 11:29:23', '2008-11-13 09:29:23', '', 217, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?page_id=219', 0, 'page', '', 0); 
