INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (326, 2, '2008-10-06 17:56:55', '2008-10-06 15:56:55', '<img src="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/textmate.png" alt="Textmate Icon" title="Textmate Icon" width="128" height="128" class="alignright reflex itiltnone size-medium wp-image-334" />Since I changed ((Why did I change? Well, besides that I like Emacs as an editor since I still like terminals and shells, I find it quite more convenient to use a tool that tries to support you in doing lots of things "automagically" instead of just write what you type. OF course, emacs can that do too, but it takes way more time for me than in TextMate. Those mentioned things are for me e.g. a shortcut, that creates a skelleton for a function or a whole module.)) from using <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/">Emacs</a> to development our Erlang homeworks to using <a href="http://macromates.com/">TextMate</a>, I\'d like to post some goodies to make Erlang and generel Development more comfort, at least for myself. <!--more-->\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I like to use the syntax highlighting theme <a href="http://www.eclips3media.com/workshop/2007/12/06/eclips3media-eclm-textmate-theme/">Eclips3.Media</a> which can be found at guys of <a href="http://www.eclips3media.com/">Eclips3.media (ECLM)</a>. Below you can see a screenshot how the theme looks like. What I like about it so much, is the combination of a dark background, the nicely "modern" shiny colors and the hiding visual affect of the comments. A dark background is very nice, especially at night of with less light around. It doesn\'t annoy your eyes so much, but it\'s not black, which would make a too strong contrast with the code. The colorful syntax highlighting is very nice chosen. It gives a very high contrast to the comments, which you can read, when you want to, but will stay hidden, if you need to concentrate on the code.\r\n[caption id="attachment_327" align="aligncenter" width="267" caption="Textmate Syntax Highlighting Theme"]<a rel="lightbox" href="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/textmate-syntax-highlighting-theme.png"><img src="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/textmate-syntax-highlighting-theme-267x300.png" alt="Textmate Syntax Highlighting Theme" title="Textmate Syntax Highlighting Theme" width="267" height="300" class="size-medium wp-image-327" /></a>[/caption]</li>\r\n	<li>Another useful things are Bundles in TextMate. There is a <em>Command</em> bundle that compiles the actual documents module for you and gives you a report window, as shown in the screenshot below. I found this command bundle script on the website of  <a href="http://www.rsaccon.com/2007/11/easy-erlang-compiling-with-textmate.html">Roberto Saccon</a> but changed it a bit, since it didn\'t look finished yet and I changed some color and formatting things. You can download my bundle changes a new bundle here:\r\n\r\n<div class="download"><a href=\'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/build.tmcommand\'>"Build" TextMate Command Bundle</a> (4.0kb)</div>\r\n\r\nBy the way: Try to press <em>CTRL+SHIFT+T</em> for a list of todos you have to get rid off. A very nice feature already built in.\r\n[caption id="attachment_328" align="aligncenter" width="300" caption="Textmate Erlang Build Window"]<a rel="lightbox"  href="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/textmate-erlang-build-window.png"><img src="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/textmate-erlang-build-window-300x251.png" alt="Textmate Erlang Build Window" title="Textmate Erlang Build Window" width="300" height="251" class="size-medium wp-image-328" /></a>[/caption]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'TextMate goodies for Erlang development', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'textmate-gimmicks-for-erlang-development', '', '\nhttp://www.eclips3media.com/workshop/2007/12/06/eclips3media-eclm-textmate-theme/', '2008-10-06 20:58:05', '2008-10-06 18:58:05', '', 0, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=326', 0, 'post', '', 2); 
