INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (347, 2, '2008-10-31 12:15:35', '2008-10-31 10:15:35', '<img src="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2008/10/wuala_logo.png" alt="" title="Wuala Logo" width="176" height="60" class="reflex itiltnone alignright size-full wp-image-349" /><ins datetime="2008-11-13T09:07:55+00:00"><strong>Update:</strong> There is a basic REST web service API available, not much yet for sharing, but nice for browsing. If I find some free time I\'d like to start developing an iPhone application for Wuala and these basic browsing options for later extension.</ins>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://wua.la/">Wuala</a> claims itself to be a social online storage. At the moment there 23,557,669 files stored. It offers\r\n\r\n<blockquote>universal access, secure backups, and sharing. Tens of thousands of users actively store and share millions of files, all of whom have their own needs and use cases for Wuala.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nHere are some lists of <a href="http://wua.la/learn/features">features</a> and <a href="http://wua.la/learn/technology">technologies</a>.\r\n\r\nNow, if you have come so far and still don\'t have a clue what to do with it, have a look at their <a href="http://wua.la/learn/usecases">use cases</a> site. Or if you feel void or wanna have a deeper look, watch this <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3xKZ4KGkQY8">video</a>.\r\n\r\nI\'m looking forward until they supply an API as they have claimed ((\r\n\r\n<em>"API: We get a lot of requests for an API, so that others can build applications on top of Wuala. That\'s definitely one of our goals as well - it\'s on our roadmap!"</em>)) so maybe I can start implementing an App for the iPhone. <!--more-->\r\n\r\nI have done some small research on how the internal structure of the application is. All further text is based on the Mac version, so paths can and will differ:\r\n\r\nThere is a launcher bundled as a normal application which will try to find a specific folder <code>~/Library/Application Support/Wuala/Program2/Wuala.BUILDNUMBER</code> ((At the moment I write this article, my build number was <code>74</code>.)). If it can not find that, it will download or update a version from the Wula.la server <code>update1.wual.la</code>, <code>update2.wual.la</code>, <code>update3.wual.la</code>, etc. If it can find it, it will launch this application. This application which seems to be a jar container is roughly <strong>12MB</strong> big. In this container, you find all kind of Java libraries and resources. But the core application seems to be at <code>~/Library/Application Support/Wuala/Program2/Wuala.BUILDNUMBER/com/wuala</code>(<code>/application</code>). What I found a bit suspicious was the use of the <a href="http://www.divshare.com/integrate/api">DivShare API library</a> ((<a href="http://www.divshare.com/">DivShare</a> is an online storage where you can upload and download files for a certain amount of subscription fee.)), because if you decompile the class files you will find a line of code saying <pre lang="java">HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection)(new URL("http://upload.divshare.com/api/upload/")).openConnection();</pre>. I could not proof if they use this service to upload the 1GB redundant data there or if it is just a typical service they have implemented like facebook and skype including all their API library.\r\n\r\nBy the way: I\'m no hacker at all and I really appreciate the work of the wua.la team since I\'m very interested in their work and that kind of science area. And I would like to support their work wherever I can (I have no problems with advertisments). But as I was diving through the code I found a funny line of code in <code>/com/wuala/facade/dialog/preferences/advanced/AdvertisementPropertiesFacade.java</code>saying: <pre lang="java">boolean canToggleAds = user.isPro() || user.getModificationDate() < 0x9c1e2a00L;</pre> ((<em>0x9c1e2a00L</em> is hex for <em>2619222528</em> aka. Friday, November 24th 1916, 19:20:32 (GMT).)) ;-)</pre>', 'Wuala - A distributed filesystem concept', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'wuala-a-distributed-filesystem-concept', '', '', '2008-11-13 11:09:16', '2008-11-13 09:09:16', '', 0, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=347', 0, 'post', '', 6); 
