INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (402, 2, '2009-01-26 12:09:45', '2009-01-26 10:09:45', 'Well, since I a very strange behaviour on my system next to these two ones ((Problem 1: I have the official Java 1.6 JDK and SDK installed on my system. When I try to type text into a standard Java AWT/Swing Textfield I can\'t insert by typing but by copy\'n\'paste. It works in other Java graphic libraries like SWT.)) ((Problem 2: Safari (3.2.1) seems to have big problems with obtaining a fast DNS response while looking for web sites. Also related to that is, that I can\'t stay logged in into Facebook for more than 5 seconds.)) ((Problem 3: When I download a file in Sarafi, my download window pops open get the focus and I can\'t set the focus back to the Safari window under ~3 seconds. A problem by some plugins? Glims http://www.machangout.com/? SafariStand http://hetima.com/safari/stand-e.html ?)) (any help on these is highly appreciated) is the fact that I very often just loose my custom keyboard shortcuts I set for some of my apps. Well, let\'s write a short agenda to let you see, how I went through this simple stuff, leading to crazy outcomes. And by the end you will see, that this - loosing it\'s keyboard shortcuts - is a real bug in the OS X system. <!--more-->\r\n\r\n<h3>Keyboard shortcuts</h3>\r\nIn OS X you have a very nice <strong>global</strong> way of assigning or changing almost every program menu bar item in every standard OS X (Cocoa) application. This can be done by <em>Preferences... -> Keyboard & Mouse -> Keyboard Shortcuts</em>. You just have to write the exact menu item name and assign a shortcut.\r\n\r\n<h3>Finding keyboard shortcuts preference file</h3>\r\nWell, here starts the problem. I couldn\'t find anything on google (or didn\'t search for the correct terms) that shows me the path to the keys. So I started to look at the most typical path: <em>~/Library</em>. But no result. So I went on with the hard and long way. Since it wasn\'t urgent to get the path, I just assigned a strange keyboard shortcut ("WHERE_ARE_YOU") and did a global hard drive search with this command: <pre lang="sh">grep -r -l -a "WHERE_ARE_YOU" ~/Library/Preferences/ > found.txt</pre> which searches the whole user directory (<code>~</code>) recursively (<code>-r</code>) even in binary files (<code>-a</code>) and put it into a search result file (<code>found.txt</code>) including the matched file names (<code>-l</code>). Sure this is basic stuff almost everybody out there nowadays knows. But what would be a nice add-on is playing a sound file at the end of the search, since this search can take lots(!) of time. And as usual - the reason why I like it so much is - OS X has already a little program for that called <em>afplay</em> ((afplay - Audio File Play uses Core Audio to play almost any audio file supported by quicktime using a resource slim way and can be found at <em>/usr/bin/</em>)). Since the typical glass sound is used as an indicator of a finished job I used this sound file leading me to the final result command: <pre lang="sh">grep -r -l -a "WHERE_ARE_YOU" ~/Library/Preferences/ > found.txt ; afplay /System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff</pre>. So now I will get nice sound when the long search is finished.\r\n\r\nAfter running this (should only take a few seconds) I came to the conclusion, that keyboard shortcuts are stored in the Preference file of the application it is binded to(!) in the user\'s profile preferences folder <em>~/Library/Preferences</em> with the plist entry: <code>NSUserKeyEquivalents</code>. So you can find a list of all keyboard shortcuts with this command: <pre lang="sh">defaults find NSUserKeyEquivalents</pre>.\r\n\r\n<h3>Various other ideas</h3>\r\nAnother idea after that is invoked by my often asked question: Is my sort-of-standard password somewhere hard coded written in any file on my hard drive? So I used the same command with a different grep string.\r\n\r\n<h3>Loosing the shortcuts in some circumstances</h3>\r\nAs discussed in <a href="http://forums.macosxhints.com/archive/index.php/t-58641.html">this thread</a> the shortcuts get lost by many users, not only me. Especially this part is nice info:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>I did a quick test by moving the com.apple.universalaccess.plist file to another location, launching the Keyboard pref pane, and the list of applications was empty. I quit System Preferences, replace the .plist file (overwriting the new one that was automatically created in the Preferences folder) and launching the Keyboard pref pane again, and sure enough, there\'s the list of applications.\r\n\r\nSo, my take on it is that the application needs listed in the universal access plist file for the pref pane to read it. If it exists there, then it goes and reads the defaults from those apps, and displays them. And then is saves them when the pane is quit. But if somehow the app is not listed in the universal access plist, but it has some key equivalents specified, then the pane does not display them, while the app still has the binding. Trouble arises when you go to add a new binding to such an app; the new entry in the universal access plist cause the app\'s plist to get modified, without retaining the information that was already in there.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThere also was the answer to the question, where to find the keys.\r\n\r\n<h3>Backup your keyboard shortcuts</h3>\r\nSo, to add a keyboard shortcut manually you could use the command line and type: <pre lang="sh">defaults write com.<company_name>.<product_name> NSUserKeyEquivalents -dict-add <menuitem_text> <keyboard_shortcut></keyboard_shortcut></menuitem_text></product_name></company_name></pre>. You can also write a small shell script to automatically write your saved keyboard shortcuts.\r\n\r\nBut now to the backup: Attached you can find a PHP class with a short script that will search for the shortcuts, parse the list and returns a shell script to automatically import your shortcuts. Here is the short script:\r\n<pre lang="php">$US = new NSUserKeys();\r\n$US->generateShellScript();\r\n#$US->generateList();</pre>\r\n\r\n<div class="download"><strong>Download</strong><a href=\'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/nsuserkeysphp.zip\'>NSUserKeys.php.zip</a></div>\r\n', 'Saving your custom keyboard shortcuts', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'saving-your-custom-keyboard-shortcuts', '', '', '2009-01-28 14:55:11', '2009-01-28 12:55:11', '', 0, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=402', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
