l hard drive search with this command: <code lang="sh">grep -R -U "WHERE_ARE_YOU" / > found.txt</code> which searches the whole hard drive (<code>/</code>) recursively (<code>-R</code>) even in binary files (<code>-U</code>) and put it into a search result file (<code>found.txt</code>). Sure this is basic stuff almost everybody out there nowadays knows. But what would be a nice add-on is playing a sound file at the end of the search, since this search can take lots(!) of time. And as usual - the reason why I like it so much is - OS X has already a little program for that called <em>afplay</em> ((afplay - Audio File Play uses Core Audio to play almost any audio file supported by quicktime using a resource slim way and can be found at <em>/usr/bin/</em>)). Since the typical glass sound is used as an indicator of a finished job I used this sound file leading me to the final result command: <code lang="sh">grep -R -U "WHERE_ARE_YOU" / > found.txt ; afplay /System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff</code>. So now I will get nice sound when the long search is finished.\r\n\r\n<h3>Various other ideas</h3>\r\nAnother idea after that is invoked by my often asked question: Is my sort-of-standard password somewhere hard coded written in any file on my hard drive? So I used the same command with a different grep string.', 'Saving your custom keyboard shortcuts', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '402-revision-3', '', '', '2009-01-26 12:08:39', '2009-01-26 10:08:39', '', 402, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=405', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
