h, I just assigned a strange keyboard shortcut ("WHERE_ARE_YOU") and did a global hard drive search with this command: <pre lang="sh">grep -r -l -a "WHERE_ARE_YOU" ~/Library/Preferences/ > found.txt</pre> which searches the whole user directory (<code>~</code>) recursively (<code>-r</code>) even in binary files (<code>-a</code>) and put it into a search result file (<code>found.txt</code>) including the matched file names (<code>-l</code>). Sure this is basic stuff almost everybody out there nowadays knows. But what would be a nice add-on is playing a sound file at the end of the search, since this search can take lots(!) of time. And as usual - the reason why I like it so much is - OS X has already a little program for that called <em>afplay</em> ((afplay - Audio File Play uses Core Audio to play almost any audio file supported by quicktime using a resource slim way and can be found at <em>/usr/bin/</em>)). Since the typical glass sound is used as an indicator of a finished job I used this sound file leading me to the final result command: <pre lang="sh">grep -r -l -a "WHERE_ARE_YOU" ~/Library/Preferences/ > found.txt ; afplay /System/Library/Sounds/Glass.aiff</pre>. So now I will get nice sound when the long search is finished.\r\n\r\nAfter running this (should only take a few seconds) I came to the conclusion, that keyboard shortcuts are stored in the Preference file of the application it is binded to(!) in the user\'s profile preferences folder <em>~/Library/Preferences</em> with the plist entry: <code>NSUserKeyEquivalents</code>. So you can find a list of all keyboard shortcuts with this command: <pre lang="sh">defaults find NSUserKeyEquivalents</pre>.\r\n\r\n<h3>Various other ideas</h3>\r\nAnother idea after that is invoked by my often asked question: Is my sort-of-standard password somewhere hard coded written in any file on my hard drive? So I used the same command with a different grep string.\r\n\r\n<h3>Loosing the shortcuts in some circumstances</h3>\r\nAs discussed in <a href="http://forums.macosxhints.com/archive/index.php/t-58641.html">this thread</a> the shortcuts get lost by many users, not only me. Especially this part is nice info:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>I did a quick test by moving the com.apple.universalaccess.plist file to another location, launching the Keyboard pref pane, and the list of applications was empty. I quit System Preferences, replace the .plist file (overwriting the new one that was automatically created in the Preferences folder) and launching the Keyboard pref pane again, and sure enough, there\'s the list of applications.\r\n\r\nSo, my take on it is that the application needs listed in the universal access plist file for the pref pane to read it. If it exists there, then it goes and reads the defaults from those apps, and displays them. And then is saves them when the pane is quit. But if somehow the app is not listed in the universal access plist, but it has some key equivalents specified, then the pane does not display them, while the app still has the binding. Trouble arises when you go to add a new binding to such an app; the new entry in the universal access plist cause the app\'s plist to get modified, without retaining the information that was already in there.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThere also was the answer to the question, where to find the keys.\r\n\r\n<h3>Backup your keyboard shortcuts</h3>\r\nSo, to add a keyboard shortcut manually you could use the command line and type: <pre lang="sh">defaults write com.<company_name>.<product_name> NSUserKeyEquivalents -dict-add <menuitem_text> <keyboard_shortcut></keyboard_shortcut></menuitem_text></product_name></company_name></pre>. You can also write a small shell script to automatically write your saved keyboard shortcuts.\r\n\r\nBut now to the backup: Attached you can find a PHP class with a short script that will search for the shortcuts, parse the list and returns a shell script to automatically import your shortcuts. Here is the short script:\r\n<pre lang="php">$US = new NSUserKeys();\r\n$US->generateShellScript();\r\n#$US->generateList();</pre>\r\n\r\n<div class="download"><a href=\'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/nsuserkeysphp.zip\'>NSUserKeys.php.zip</a></div>\r\n', 'Saving your custom keyboard shortcuts', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '402-revision-10', '', '', '2009-01-28 14:53:31', '2009-01-28 12:53:31', '', 402, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=414', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (415, 2, '2009-01-29 14:48:55', '2009-01-29 12:48:55', '<img alt="" src="http://kompics.sics.se/images/Kompics-newlogo-small.png" title="KompICS Logo" class="alignright" width="150" height="37" />Well, we got a new Java Framework for our course <a href="http://www.ict.kth.se/courses/ID2203/">Distributed Systems, Advanced Course</a> called <a href="http://kompics.sics.se/">KompICS</a> ((KTH Reactive Component Model for Distributed Computing)). It seems to be quite nice for simulating and abstracting distributed environment and create scenarios for it, although I have to dive deeper to validate. But as quite often on the Mac side of the Java world there is some trouble. This time - the classic: <!--more-->\r\n\r\n<h3>Running 32-bit classes on a 64-bit Runtime Environment</h3>\r\n...impossible. The KompICS framework comes in library packaged as JARs but compiled for 32-bit. So what we need to do is recompiling the source code found <a href="http://kompics.sics.se/trac/browser/trunk">here</a>. Therefore we need <a href="http://maven.apache.org/">Maven</a>. After compiling the code on a 64-bit system like Leopard ((Mac OS X Leopard (10.5) comes only with the <a href="http://www.apple.com/macosx/technology/64bit.html">64-bit version of the 1.6</a> JRE and Java SDK.)) you get several JARs that you can integrate in your project.\r\n\r\n<pre lang="sh">$ sudo port install subversion maven2\r\n$ svn checkout svn://small.sics.se/kompics/trunk kompics\r\n$ cd kompics\r\n$ mvn install</pre>\r\n\r\n<div class="info"><strong>Update 1:</strong> KompICS can\'t be built with Maven without the plugin that downloads missing JARs from the Maven repository to your local one called <a href="http://maven.apache.org/plugins/maven-resources-plugin/usage.html">Resources Plugin</a>. <em>(- thanks Eric)</em></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="exclamation"><strong>Update 2:</strong> There is a small bug in the Maven <a link="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Maven#The_POM">POM</a> main file: One component (<code>process-launcher</code>) is inserted in the Maven POM file as a module but does not exist in the source folders. So you have to modify the main POM file. <em>(- thanks Eric)</em></div>\r\n\r\nHere I have the final package compiled; thanks to Eric for running the actual compiling.\r\n\r\n<div class="download"><strong>Download:</strong> <a href=\'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/kompics-bundle.zip\'>kompics-bundle</a> <em>1.3mb</em></div>', 'Running KompICS on a 64-bit Java Leopard', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'running-kompics-on-a-64-bit-java-leopard', '', '', '2009-01-29 15:33:14', '2009-01-29 13:33:14', '', 0, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=415', 0, 'post', '', 3); 
