INSERT INTO `v4_wp_posts` VALUES (431, 2, '2009-06-10 21:31:53', '2009-06-10 19:31:53', '<img src="http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/xargs.png" alt="Xargs" title="Xargs" width="150" height="104" class="alignright size-full wp-image-424" /> Well, as we work in project teams day-in day-out at KTH, we use SVN ((I really would like to test <a href="http://bazaar-vcs.org/">Bazaar</a> as a distributed versioning protocol but our collaboration page <a href="http://www.assembla.com/">Assembla</a> just supports <a href="http://subversion.tigris.org/">SVN</a> and <a href="http://git-scm.com/">Git</a> at the moment.)) as our collaboration platform. But when grapping SVN code as starting point and then shifting it over to our own SVN brings up a problem: We have to get rid of the hidden <code>.svn</code> folders (otherwise NetBeans or Eclipse too?) will not sync the corresponding code folders. So how to do that? <!--more-->\n\nEither you use the nice small widget by Matthew Hansen called <a href="http://studentwebs.winona.edu/mahansen2573/Matthew.Hansen/Widgets.html">Hiden Files</a> for Mac\'s Dashboard to show these folders and delete them by one by one hand, or you to the old school version and use a terminal with the help of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xargs">Xargs</a> ;-) But what is the right command line for that? There you go:\n\n<pre lang="bash">find . -name ".svn" -type d | xargs rm -r</pre>\nfind . -name ".svn" -type d -exec rm -rf {} \\;\n\nYou have to (1) first search for the folders and then (2) batch delete them.\n\nXargs does a real nice job here because it takes every found entry and runs a command on each of those lines. \n\nYou may ask why not just use find\'s <code>-exec</code> option like this?\n\n<pre lang="bash">find . -name ".svn -exec rm -r \'{}\' \\;</pre>\n\n Well, first of all because I always forget the syntax and it becomes no use if you want to put a grep first after the find and then do a batch job. ((I also read that in old find versions it is not as performant as xargs because it will trigger then command directly after each found line instead of a real batch job.))', 'Xargs - Old school batch processing', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '425-autosave', '', '', '2009-06-10 21:31:53', '2009-06-10 19:31:53', '', 425, 'http://www.kreisquadratur.de/blog/?p=431', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
